      <body>
         <div type="edition"
              ana="#b1"
              xml:lang="grc"
              subtype="transcription"
              xml:id="zoor0356.transcription"
              corresp="#zoor0356.translation">
            <p>+ <lb/>
               <choice>
                  <sic>Μνημῖον</sic>
                  <corr>Μνημεῖον</corr>
               </choice> Ὄββης, ἀπο<lb/>θανούσης μετὰ καλῆς<lb/>
                    πίστεως καὶ καλoῦ<lb/> ὀνόματος <expan><abbr>ἐτ</abbr><ex>ῶν</ex></expan> ιβʹ,<lb/> ἐν μηνὶ
                    Λῴου δʹ,<lb/> ἐν ἡμέρᾳ Κυρίου<lb/> τετάρτῃ. <choice>
                  <sic>Θάρσι</sic>
                  <corr>Θάρσει</corr>
               </choice>, <choice>
                  <sic>οὐ<lb/>δὶς</sic>
                  <corr>οὐδεὶς</corr>
               </choice> ἀθάνατος.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="translation"
              ana="#b1"
              xml:id="zoor0356.translation"
              corresp="#zoor0356.transcription">
            <p> Monument of Obbe, who died having a good faith and good name (at the age) of 12
                    years, on (the) 4th (day) of (the) month Loos, on the fourth day of (the) Lord
                    (Wednesday). Be of good cheer, no one (is) immortal.</p>
         </div>
      </body>
      <back>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>No year of death is listed on the inscription, but it has been dated to the second quarter of the fifth century CE on the strength of other factors. The inscription does record the day of the month and the month, as well as the day of the week, providing the fourth day of the Lord (Wednesday), the 4th day of the month Loos, that is, July 23. The tombstone is one of about 700 discovered in Byzantine Zoora. The majority of the Greek tombstones from this location have been identified as Christian. This inscription has not been fully published. The text and frame surrounding it are engraved. An engraved cross is found in the middle, above the frame.</p>
         </div>
